VALUES
(41, 7, 25, 42, 17, 16, 16, 'fell at his feet', 'Expressions of Humility and Gratitude', 'This connection highlights the act of falling at Jesus'' feet, which signifies humility and reverence in both passages. The woman in Mark seeks help for her daughter, while the Samaritan in Luke expresses gratitude.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 25, 66, 22, 8, 9, 'fell at his feet', 'Falling at Feet', 'This connection highlights the act of falling at someone''s feet in both passages. In Mark, the woman falls at Jesus'' feet, while in Revelation, John falls at the feet of the angel. Both instances reflect a posture of humility and reverence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 26, 40, 15, 22, 22, NULL, 'Connection of Healing Requests', 'Both passages emphasize a woman seeking help for her daughter who is afflicted by a devil. The descriptions of the woman''s nationality and her plea for mercy create a parallel in their narratives.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 26, 23, 49, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Nations and Healing', 'This connection highlights the inclusion of nations beyond Israel in God''s plan. The Syrophenician woman represents those from ''far'' nations seeking healing, paralleling Isaiah''s mention of those coming from distant lands.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 26, 48, 3, 28, 28, 'a Greek, a Syrophenician by nation', 'Unity Beyond Ethnic Boundaries', 'This connection highlights the inclusion of a Greek woman in Mark, paralleling Galatians'' assertion that there is neither Jew nor Greek. Both passages emphasize the breaking down of ethnic barriers in the context of faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 26, 51, 3, 11, 11, 'a Greek, a Syrophenician by nation', 'Unity Beyond Ethnic Boundaries', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of the Greek, highlighting that in Christ, ethnic distinctions are transcended. The Syrophenician woman''s plea illustrates the breaking down of barriers, which is echoed in the declaration of unity in Christ found in Colossians.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 27, 40, 15, 23, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Faith and Inclusion', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''It is not meet to take the children’s bread, and to cast it to dogs.'' This connection highlights the dialogue between Jesus and the Canaanite woman, illustrating her faith and the theme of inclusion beyond Israel.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 27, 40, 7, 6, 6, 'dogs', 'Connection of ''dogs'' Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''dogs'' in relation to the sacred. In Mark, Jesus refers to ''dogs'' in the context of prioritizing the children, while Matthew warns against giving what is holy to ''dogs''.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 27, 44, 22, 21, 21, 'children’s bread', 'Children and Gentiles', 'This connection highlights the transition from focusing on the children of Israel to the inclusion of the Gentiles. Jesus'' statement about the children and dogs reflects the initial priority of the Jewish people, while the command to send Paul to the Gentiles signifies a shift towards broader inclusion.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 27, 49, 2, 12, 12, 'children’s bread', 'Children and Strangers Theme', 'This connection highlights the distinction between the children of Israel and those outside the covenant. Both passages emphasize the idea of being ''without'' or excluded from God''s promises.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 27, 45, 15, 8, 8, 'the children’s bread', 'Connection of Jesus'' Ministry Focus', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' initial focus on the children of Israel, as indicated in Mark 7:27, and His role as a minister to the circumcision in Romans 15:8. Both passages emphasize the priority of God''s promises to the Jewish people.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 28, 45, 10, 12, 12, 'dogs under the table eat', 'Inclusivity of God''s Grace', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusivity in God''s grace. Both passages emphasize that all people, regardless of their background, can receive blessings from the Lord.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 28, 45, 3, 29, 29, 'dogs under the table', 'Inclusivity of God''s Grace', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s grace extending beyond Israel. The reference to ''dogs under the table'' in Mark suggests that even those considered outsiders can receive blessings, paralleling Romans'' assertion that God is also for the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 28, 23, 45, 22, 22, NULL, 'Universal Call to Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusivity in salvation. Both passages emphasize that God''s grace extends beyond Israel, inviting all people to partake in His mercy.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 28, 42, 15, 30, 32, NULL, 'Theme of Inclusion and Grace', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusion and grace towards those considered outsiders. In Mark, the woman acknowledges her place as a ''dog'' yet seeks crumbs, while in Luke, the father celebrates the return of his lost son, emphasizing acceptance and joy for all. Both passages illustrate the expansive nature of God''s mercy.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 28, 44, 11, 17, 18, 'the dogs under the table', 'Gentiles and God''s Grace', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusion, as both passages address the acceptance of those outside the Jewish community. The phrase ''the dogs under the table'' in Mark reflects the initial view of Gentiles, while Acts emphasizes that God granted ''repentance unto life'' to them.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 28, 42, 7, 6, 8, NULL, 'Authority and Worthiness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of worthiness and authority in approaching Jesus. The woman in Mark acknowledges her unworthiness yet seeks healing, while the centurion in Luke expresses his own unworthiness and understanding of authority in requesting healing for his servant.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 28, 19, 145, 16, 16, 'the dogs under the table eat', 'Divine Provision and Satisfaction', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine provision, where both passages emphasize the idea of God satisfying needs. In Mark, the crumbs represent the sustenance available even to those outside the main recipients, while Psalms speaks of God satisfying the desires of all living things.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 29, 40, 5, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual need and deliverance. In Mark 7:29, the healing of the daughter signifies a response to a plea for help, paralleling the blessing of the ''poor in spirit'' in Matthew 5:3, who recognize their need for divine assistance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 29, 23, 66, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Humility', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of a humble spirit. In Mark, the healing of the daughter reflects a response to faith, while Isaiah highlights God''s attention to those with a contrite spirit. This connection highlights the theme of divine favor towards the humble.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 29, 40, 8, 9, 13, 'the devil is gone out of thy daughter', 'Faith and Healing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith leading to healing. In both passages, Jesus responds to the faith of individuals, resulting in the healing of their loved ones.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 29, 23, 57, 15, 16, 'the devil is gone out of thy daughter', 'Healing and Humility Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of revival and healing in both passages. Mark 7:29 speaks to the healing of a daughter, while Isaiah 57:15-16 emphasizes reviving the humble and contrite spirit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 29, 62, 3, 8, 8, 'the devil is gone out', 'Connection of Deliverance from Evil', 'Both passages emphasize the defeat of the devil. In Mark 7:29, the devil is cast out, while 1 John 3:8 speaks of the Son of God destroying the works of the devil.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 30, 43, 4, 50, 52, NULL, 'Healing of Children', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing in both passages, where Jesus restores the health of children. In Mark, the daughter is found well, while in John, the son is confirmed to be alive and recovering.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 30, 62, 3, 8, 8, 'the devil gone out', 'Connection of Deliverance and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the defeat of the devil''s influence. In Mark, the devil is gone out, while in 1 John, the purpose of the Son of God is to destroy the works of the devil.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 31, 41, 5, 20, 20, 'coasts of Decapolis', 'Connection Between Decapolis References', 'Both passages emphasize the region of Decapolis, highlighting its significance in Jesus'' ministry. In Mark 5:20, the man publishes what Jesus has done in Decapolis, while Mark 7:31 mentions Jesus'' journey through this area.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 31, 40, 4, 25, 25, 'coasts of Decapolis', 'Geographical Connection in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the region of Decapolis, highlighting its significance in Jesus'' ministry. Mark notes Jesus'' journey through Decapolis, while Matthew mentions the multitudes from this area following Him.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 31, 40, 15, 29, 31, 'sea of Galilee', 'Healing Miracles of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' ministry near the sea of Galilee, where he performs healing miracles. The mention of the multitude in Matthew aligns with the context of Jesus'' activities in Mark, highlighting his compassion and power.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 31, 41, 7, 24, 24, NULL, 'Journey Through Tyre and Sidon', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement through Tyre and Sidon, highlighting his travels in the region. This connection illustrates the geographical context of his ministry as he moves towards the Sea of Galilee.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 7, 31, 40, 11, 21, 21, 'Tyre and Sidon', 'Connection of Tyre and Sidon', 'Both passages emphasize Tyre and Sidon as significant locations. Mark mentions Jesus'' journey through the coasts of Tyre and Sidon, while Matthew contrasts these cities with Chorazin and Bethsaida, highlighting their unrepentance despite witnessing miracles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
